cs.CR, cs.IT, cs.DM, cs.SI, cs.CC

The paper's title and abstract suggest that it is about cryptography, specifically public key exchange protocols. Therefore, cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) is the most likely sub-category. The use of algebraic structures such as homomorphisms and tropical algebras suggests that the paper may also fall under cs.IT (Information Theory) and cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics). The paper's focus on efficiency may also place it under cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) and cs.CC (Computational Complexity).
